{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646541"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:32:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:32:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18189"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18189"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.13,0.04,0.08,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79339"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10903"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18189"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64661"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25351"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25354"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79339"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe intervertebral disc consists of two main components: the nucleus pulposus and the annulus fibrosus. These structures work together to allow movement between vertebrae while maintaining spinal stability.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the nucleus pulposus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Absorbs shock and provides flexibility","Anchors adjacent vertebrae together","Forms concentric rings of fibrocartilage","Supplies nutrients to vertebral bodies","Produces red blood cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsorbs shock and provides flexibility\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the nucleus pulposus. This gelatinous core contains proteoglycans that attract and bind water, creating a hydraulic system that helps distribute forces evenly across the vertebral endplates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnchors adjacent vertebrae together\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a function of the annulus fibrosus and spinal ligaments\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms concentric rings of fibrocartilage\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the structure of the annulus fibrosus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupplies nutrients to vertebral bodies\u003C/strong\u003E - Nutrients are supplied via blood vessels, not through the nucleus pulposus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduces red blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs in red bone marrow, not in intervertebral discs\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe nucleus pulposus acts like a water-filled cushion that deforms under pressure, allowing the spine to bend and twist while absorbing compressive forces.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The nucleus pulposus is the gelatinous inner core of the intervertebral disc that provides flexibility and shock absorption.","The nucleus pulposus contains proteoglycans that attract water, enabling the disc to resist compressive forces.","The annulus fibrosus surrounds and contains the nucleus pulposus, providing structural support to the intervertebral disc."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64661"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18189"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64661"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T10:11:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T10:12:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10903"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79339"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.c